gr.forth.ics.util
Class FastLinkedList<E>

java.lang.Object
  java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      java.util.AbstractList<E>
          java.util.AbstractSequentialList<E>
              gr.forth.ics.util.FastLinkedList<E>
Type Parameters:
E - the type of the elements contained in the list
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable, Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, List<E>
public class FastLinkedList<E>
extends AbstractSequentialList<E>
implements Serializable

A linked list that also provides pointers to list nodes, making it possible for several operations to be of constant time instead of linear.

For example, consider a list containing arbitrary Nodes: 

 class Node {
      Accessor<Node> accessor;
      //other members here
 }
 
 FastLinkedList<Node> list = new FastLinkedList<Node>();
 Node node = ...;
 Accessor<Node> accessor = list.addFirst(node);
 node.accessor = accessor;
If there is a need to later remove this node from the list, instead of the usual operation: 
 list.remove(node);
which would take linear time as it involves searching through the list for the element, this can be used, since the accessor to the element is available: 
 node.accessor.remove();
which takes constant time.

Also, linked lists can be appended together to produce a single list, in O(1) time. The list that is appended to the tail of another becomes permanently empty, and all operations attempting to insert an element will throw an IllegalStatementException.

This implementation allows structural modifications while iterations are in progress, without throwing ConcurrentModificationException.

isConsumed

public boolean isConsumed()
Returns whether this list has been appended to another one. If this is the case, then this list will always be empty, and throw IllegalStateException for all operations trying to modify it; essentially after being appended, the list is a throw-away object.

append

public void append(FastLinkedList<E> list)
Appends the elements of a list to this one (in constant time). To preserve consistency, the other list is turned to an empty immutable list, and its isConsumed() method will return true. The other list should be thrown away after this operation.

Parameters:
list - the list to be appended to this one

ownsAccessor

public boolean ownsAccessor(Accessor<E> accessor)
Returns whether the given accessor is owned by this list. For this to be true, the accessor must have been created by this list, and its respective element must not have been removed by any means.
